Now my knowledge of RN is very rudimentary, but if my understanding is correct, this in RN has a very different scope that other languages. Again, further assuming my understanding is correct, this in the above example refers to styles, and therefore does not see the myColor prop in the class. So my question is: how do you reference the actual class? Or is referring to the class from the style sheet considered bad practice and should be avoided entirely? (and if this is the case, what is the "good" practice?) Thanks,

A:

If you have predefined colors then use it in constants 
If you want to change the colors on some events then maintain it in state variable
Sample code: 
import React, { Component } from 'react';
import { StyleSheet, Text, View } from 'react-native';
const myColor = 'blue'
export default class LotsOfStyles extends Component {

 constructor(props) {
 super(props);
 this.state = ({ color: 'red' })
 }

 render() {
 return (
 <View>
 <Text style={styles.myStyle}>Lorem Ipsum</Text>
 <Text style={[styles.myStyle, { color: this.state.color }]}>Lorem Ipsum</Text>
 </View>
 );
 }
}

const styles = StyleSheet.create({
 myStyle: {
 color: myColor,
 fontWeight: 'bold',
 fontSize: 30,
 },
});

